    {
        "content": "<p>By default lean assumes 1 and 2 are naturals, and it can't figure out how to divide a natural by a natural and get an element of J. That's what the error message says. (Edit: I've just realised you're that guy I met a week or two ago who is a Haskell whizz, apologies, I'm sure you can read the error messages!). If you mean the 1 and 2 in \\Q you can write <code>(1 : \\Q)</code> etc.</p>",
        "id": 477936377,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1729466741
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But even then you'll get an error because a term of type J is not a rational, it's a pair consisting of a rational and a proof</p>",
        "id": 477936492,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1729466824
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">check</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">F6</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">λ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">λ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ω</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"bp\">/</span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"bp\">/</span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">norm_num</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>works. <code>norm_num</code> proves the theorem <code>0 ≤ 1 / 2 ∧ 1 / 2 ≤ 1</code> which is the proof you need to make the full term of type J. The pointy brackets are the constructor for J.</p>",
        "id": 477936694,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1729467038
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Because Lean is expecting a term of type <code>J</code> at the end there, it's expecting a rational at the point where I write 1/2 so it decides that 1 and 2 should be rationals too, which is what you want. The reason it went for naturals when you tried it was that it didn't have a clue what to expect because J has no division defined on it, so it fell back on the default 1 and 2, which are naturals.</p>",
        "id": 477937148,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1729467553
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Great answer - thanks very much - I should be used to type defaulting you are right - the proof requirements on the other hand (that 1/2 is actually between 0 and 1) are less familiar.</p>",
